Note:
Runa Standard Library: Logging Module

Provides comprehensive logging capabilities for applications with multiple log levels,
formatters, handlers, and AI-friendly interfaces. Supports structured logging,
performance monitoring, and integration with AI systems.

Features:
- Multiple log levels (DEBUG, INFO, WARNING, ERROR, CRITICAL)
- Configurable formatters and handlers
- Structured logging with metadata
- Performance monitoring and metrics
- AI-friendly interfaces and annotations
- Thread-safe logging
- File, console, and network handlers
:End Note

Note: Core Types and Constants
Type LogLevel is:
    | DEBUG
    | INFO
    | WARNING
    | ERROR
    | CRITICAL

Type LogRecord is Dictionary with:
    timestamp as Float
    level as LogLevel
    logger_name as String
    message as String
    module as String
    function as String
    line as Integer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]
    exception_info as Optional[String]
    performance_metrics as Optional[Dictionary[String, Float]]

Type LogFormatter is Dictionary with:
    format_string as String
    include_timestamp as Boolean defaults to true
    include_level as Boolean defaults to true
    include_logger as Boolean defaults to true
    include_location as Boolean defaults to true
    include_metadata as Boolean defaults to false
    include_performance as Boolean defaults to false
    timestamp_format as String defaults to "ISO"
    color_output as Boolean defaults to false

Type LogHandler is Dictionary with:
    formatter as LogFormatter
    level as LogLevel
    enabled as Boolean defaults to true
    handler_type as String  Note: "console", "file", "network", "ai"
    handler_config as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type Logger is Dictionary with:
    name as String
    level as LogLevel
    handlers as List[LogHandler]
    parent as Optional[Logger]
    propagate as Boolean defaults to true
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Note: Log Level Utilities
Process called "get_level_name" that takes level as LogLevel returns String:
    Match level:
        When DEBUG:
            Return "DEBUG"
        When INFO:
            Return "INFO"
        When WARNING:
            Return "WARNING"
        When ERROR:
            Return "ERROR"
        When CRITICAL:
            Return "CRITICAL"

Process called "get_level_value" that takes level as LogLevel returns Integer:
    Match level:
        When DEBUG:
            Return 10
        When INFO:
            Return 20
        When WARNING:
            Return 30
        When ERROR:
            Return 40
        When CRITICAL:
            Return 50

Process called "parse_level" that takes level_name as String returns Optional[LogLevel]:
    If level_name is equal to "DEBUG":
        Return Some with value as DEBUG
    Otherwise if level_name is equal to "INFO":
        Return Some with value as INFO
    Otherwise if level_name is equal to "WARNING":
        Return Some with value as WARNING
    Otherwise if level_name is equal to "ERROR":
        Return Some with value as ERROR
    Otherwise if level_name is equal to "CRITICAL":
        Return Some with value as CRITICAL
    Otherwise:
        Return None

Process called "is_enabled" that takes logger_level as LogLevel and message_level as LogLevel returns Boolean:
    Return get_level_value with level as message_level is greater than or equal to get_level_value with level as logger_level

Note: Formatter Functions
Process called "create_default_formatter" that returns LogFormatter:
    Return LogFormatter with:
        format_string as "{timestamp} [{level}] {logger}: {message}"
        include_timestamp as true
        include_level as true
        include_logger as true
        include_location as false
        include_metadata as false
        include_performance as false
        timestamp_format as "ISO"
        color_output as false

Process called "create_ai_formatter" that returns LogFormatter:
    Return LogFormatter with:
        format_string as "AI_LOG: {timestamp} [{level}] {logger} | {message} | {metadata}"
        include_timestamp as true
        include_level as true
        include_logger as true
        include_location as true
        include_metadata as true
        include_performance as true
        timestamp_format as "ISO"
        color_output as true

Process called "create_json_formatter" that returns LogFormatter:
    Return LogFormatter with:
        format_string as "JSON"
        include_timestamp as true
        include_level as true
        include_logger as true
        include_location as true
        include_metadata as true
        include_performance as true
        timestamp_format as "ISO"
        color_output as false

Process called "format_record" that takes record as LogRecord and formatter as LogFormatter returns String:
    If formatter.format_string is equal to "JSON":
        Return format_json_record with record as record and formatter as formatter
    Otherwise:
        Return format_text_record with record as record and formatter as formatter

Process called "format_text_record" that takes record as LogRecord and formatter as LogFormatter returns String:
    Let result be formatter.format_string
    
    If formatter.include_timestamp:
        Let timestamp_str be format_timestamp with timestamp as record.timestamp and format as formatter.timestamp_format
        Set result to replace_string with string as result and old as "{timestamp}" and new as timestamp_str
    
    If formatter.include_level:
        Let level_str be get_level_name with level as record.level
        If formatter.color_output:
            Let color_code be get_level_color with level as record.level
            Set level_str to color_code plus level_str plus "\033[0m"
        Set result to replace_string with string as result and old as "{level}" and new as level_str
    
    If formatter.include_logger:
        Set result to replace_string with string as result and old as "{logger}" and new as record.logger_name
    
    Set result to replace_string with string as result and old as "{message}" and new as record.message
    
    If formatter.include_location:
        Let location_str be record.module plus ":" plus record.function plus ":" plus record.line
        Set result to replace_string with string as result and old as "{location}" and new as location_str
    
    If formatter.include_metadata and length of keys of record.metadata is greater than 0:
        Let metadata_str be format_metadata with metadata as record.metadata
        Set result to replace_string with string as result and old as "{metadata}" and new as metadata_str
    
    If formatter.include_performance and record.performance_metrics is not None:
        Let perf_str be format_performance with metrics as record.performance_metrics
        Set result to replace_string with string as result and old as "{performance}" and new as perf_str
    
    Return result

Process called "format_json_record" that takes record as LogRecord and formatter as LogFormatter returns String:
    Let json_obj be dictionary containing:
        "timestamp" as format_timestamp with timestamp as record.timestamp and format as "ISO"
        "level" as get_level_name with level as record.level
        "logger" as record.logger_name
        "message" as record.message
        "module" as record.module
        "function" as record.function
        "line" as record.line
    
    If length of keys of record.metadata is greater than 0:
        Set json_obj["metadata"] to record.metadata
    
    If record.performance_metrics is not None:
        Set json_obj["performance"] to record.performance_metrics
    
    If record.exception_info is not None:
        Set json_obj["exception"] to record.exception_info
    
    Return serialize with value as JSONObject with fields as json_obj

Process called "format_timestamp" that takes timestamp as Float and format as String returns String:
    If format is equal to "ISO":
        Return format_iso_timestamp with timestamp as timestamp
    Otherwise if format is equal to "UNIX":
        Return timestamp
    Otherwise if format is equal to "READABLE":
        Return format_readable_timestamp with timestamp as timestamp
    Otherwise:
        Return format_iso_timestamp with timestamp as timestamp

Process called "format_metadata" that takes metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns String:
    Let parts be list containing
    For each key in keys of metadata:
        Let value be metadata at key key
        Add key plus "=" plus value to parts
    Return join_strings with strings as parts and separator as ", "

Process called "format_performance" that takes metrics as Dictionary[String, Float] returns String:
    Let parts be list containing
    For each key in keys of metrics:
        Let value be metrics at key key
        Add key plus "=" plus value plus "ms" to parts
    Return join_strings with strings as parts and separator as ", "

Process called "get_level_color" that takes level as LogLevel returns String:
    Match level:
        When DEBUG:
            Return "\033[36m"  Note: Cyan
        When INFO:
            Return "\033[32m"  Note: Green
        When WARNING:
            Return "\033[33m"  Note: Yellow
        When ERROR:
            Return "\033[31m"  Note: Red
        When CRITICAL:
            Return "\033[35m"  Note: Magenta

Note: Handler Functions
Process called "create_console_handler" that takes level as LogLevel returns LogHandler:
    Return LogHandler with:
        formatter as create_default_formatter
        level as level
        enabled as true
        handler_type as "console"
        handler_config as dictionary containing:
            "stream" as "stdout"

Process called "create_file_handler" that takes file_path as String and level as LogLevel returns LogHandler:
    Return LogHandler with:
        formatter as create_default_formatter
        level as level
        enabled as true
        handler_type as "file"
        handler_config as dictionary containing:
            "file_path" as file_path
            "mode" as "append"
            "encoding" as "utf-8"
            "max_size" as 10485760  Note: 10MB
            "backup_count" as 5

Process called "create_ai_handler" that takes level as LogLevel returns LogHandler:
    Return LogHandler with:
        formatter as create_ai_formatter
        level as level
        enabled as true
        handler_type as "ai"
        handler_config as dictionary containing:
            "model" as "gpt-4"
            "include_context" as true
            "performance_tracking" as true

Process called "create_json_handler" that takes file_path as String and level as LogLevel returns LogHandler:
    Return LogHandler with:
        formatter as create_json_formatter
        level as level
        enabled as true
        handler_type as "file"
        handler_config as dictionary containing:
            "file_path" as file_path
            "mode" as "append"
            "encoding" as "utf-8"

Process called "handle_record" that takes handler as LogHandler and record as LogRecord returns Boolean:
    If not handler.enabled:
        Return false
    
    If not is_enabled with logger_level as handler.level and message_level as record.level:
        Return false
    
    Let formatted_message be format_record with record as record and formatter as handler.formatter
    
    Match handler.handler_type:
        When "console":
            Return handle_console with message as formatted_message and config as handler.handler_config
        When "file":
            Return handle_file with message as formatted_message and config as handler.handler_config
        When "ai":
            Return handle_ai with record as record and config as handler.handler_config
        Otherwise:
            Return false

Process called "handle_console" that takes message as String and config as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Try:
        Display message
        Return true
    Catch:
        Return false

Process called "handle_file" that takes message as String and config as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Try:
        Let file_path be config at key "file_path"
        Let mode be config at key "mode"
        Let encoding be config at key "encoding"
        
        Let full_message be message plus "\n"
        Return append_to_file with path as file_path and content as full_message and encoding as encoding
    Catch:
        Return false

Process called "handle_ai" that takes record as LogRecord and config as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Try:
        Let model be config at key "model"
        Let include_context be config at key "include_context"
        Let performance_tracking be config at key "performance_tracking"
        
        Note: AI-specific logging logic would go here
        Note: This could include sending to AI monitoring systems,
        Note: performance analysis, or intelligent log aggregation
        
        Return true
    Catch:
        Return false

Note: Logger Management
Process called "create_logger" that takes name as String returns Logger:
    Return Logger with:
        name as name
        level as INFO
        handlers as list containing
        parent as None
        propagate as true
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "get_logger" that takes name as String returns Logger:
    Note: In a full implementation, this would maintain a registry of loggers
    Note: For now, always create a new logger
    Return create_logger with name as name

Process called "set_logger_level" that takes logger as Logger and level as LogLevel returns Logger:
    Set logger.level to level
    Return logger

Process called "add_handler" that takes logger as Logger and handler as LogHandler returns Logger:
    Add handler to logger.handlers
    Return logger

Process called "remove_handler" that takes logger as Logger and handler_index as Integer returns Logger:
    If handler_index is greater than or equal to 0 and handler_index is less than length of logger.handlers:
        Remove logger.handlers at index handler_index
    Return logger

Process called "clear_handlers" that takes logger as Logger returns Logger:
    Set logger.handlers to list containing
    Return logger

Note: Core Logging Functions
Process called "log" that takes logger as Logger and level as LogLevel and message as String and metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Let record be LogRecord with:
        timestamp as current_time
        level as level
        logger_name as logger.name
        message as message
        module as get_current_module
        function as get_current_function
        line as get_current_line
        metadata as metadata
        exception_info as None
        performance_metrics as None
    
    Let success be true
    
    For each handler in logger.handlers:
        Let handler_success be handle_record with handler as handler and record as record
        Set success to success and handler_success
    
    If logger.propagate and logger.parent is not None:
        Let parent_success be log with logger as logger.parent and level as level and message as message and metadata as metadata
        Set success to success and parent_success
    
    Return success

Process called "debug" that takes logger as Logger and message as String and metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Return log with logger as logger and level as DEBUG and message as message and metadata as metadata

Process called "info" that takes logger as Logger and message as String and metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Return log with logger as logger and level as INFO and message as message and metadata as metadata

Process called "warning" that takes logger as Logger and message as String and metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Return log with logger as logger and level as WARNING and message as message and metadata as metadata

Process called "error" that takes logger as Logger and message as String and metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Return log with logger as logger and level as ERROR and message as message and metadata as metadata

Process called "critical" that takes logger as Logger and message as String and metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Return log with logger as logger and level as CRITICAL and message as message and metadata as metadata

Process called "exception" that takes logger as Logger and message as String and exception_info as String and metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Let record be LogRecord with:
        timestamp as current_time
        level as ERROR
        logger_name as logger.name
        message as message
        module as get_current_module
        function as get_current_function
        line as get_current_line
        metadata as metadata
        exception_info as Some with value as exception_info
        performance_metrics as None
    
    Let success be true
    
    For each handler in logger.handlers:
        Let handler_success be handle_record with handler as handler and record as record
        Set success to success and handler_success
    
    If logger.propagate and logger.parent is not None:
        Let parent_success be exception with logger as logger.parent and message as message and exception_info as exception_info and metadata as metadata
        Set success to success and parent_success
    
    Return success

Note: Performance Monitoring
Process called "log_with_performance" that takes logger as Logger and level as LogLevel and message as String and start_time as Float and metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Let end_time be current_time
    Let duration be end_time minus start_time
    
    Let performance_metrics be dictionary containing:
        "duration_ms" as duration multiplied by 1000
        "start_time" as start_time
        "end_time" as end_time
    
    Let record be LogRecord with:
        timestamp as end_time
        level as level
        logger_name as logger.name
        message as message
        module as get_current_module
        function as get_current_function
        line as get_current_line
        metadata as metadata
        exception_info as None
        performance_metrics as Some with value as performance_metrics
    
    Let success be true
    
    For each handler in logger.handlers:
        Let handler_success be handle_record with handler as handler and record as record
        Set success to success and handler_success
    
    If logger.propagate and logger.parent is not None:
        Let parent_success be log_with_performance with logger as logger.parent and level as level and message as message and start_time as start_time and metadata as metadata
        Set success to success and parent_success
    
    Return success

Process called "time_function" that takes logger as Logger and function_name as String and function as Process returns Any:
    Let start_time be current_time
    Let metadata be dictionary containing:
        "function" as function_name
        "type" as "performance"
    
    Try:
        Let result be function
        Let success be log_with_performance with logger as logger and level as INFO and message as "Function completed" and start_time as start_time and metadata as metadata
        Return result
    Catch error:
        Let error_metadata be dictionary containing:
            "function" as function_name
            "type" as "performance"
            "error" as error.message
        Let success be log_with_performance with logger as logger and level as ERROR and message as "Function failed" and start_time as start_time and metadata as error_metadata
        Throw error

Note: AI-Specific Logging
Process called "log_ai_interaction" that takes logger as Logger and model as String and input_tokens as Integer and output_tokens as Integer and duration as Float and metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Let ai_metadata be dictionary containing:
        "model" as model
        "input_tokens" as input_tokens
        "output_tokens" as output_tokens
        "total_tokens" as input_tokens plus output_tokens
        "duration_seconds" as duration
        "tokens_per_second" as (input_tokens plus output_tokens) divided by duration
        "type" as "ai_interaction"
    
    Let combined_metadata be merge_dictionaries with dict1 as ai_metadata and dict2 as metadata
    
    Let message be "AI interaction with " plus model plus " completed"
    
    Return log_with_performance with logger as logger and level as INFO and message as message and start_time as current_time minus duration and metadata as combined_metadata

Process called "log_ai_error" that takes logger as Logger and model as String and error_type as String and error_message as String and metadata as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Let ai_metadata be dictionary containing:
        "model" as model
        "error_type" as error_type
        "type" as "ai_error"
    
    Let combined_metadata be merge_dictionaries with dict1 as ai_metadata and dict2 as metadata
    
    Let message be "AI error with " plus model plus ": " plus error_type
    
    Return exception with logger as logger and message as message and exception_info as error_message and metadata as combined_metadata

Note: Configuration and Setup
Process called "setup_default_logging" that takes log_level as LogLevel and log_file as Optional[String] returns Logger:
    Let root_logger be create_logger with name as "root"
    Set root_logger.level to log_level
    
    Let console_handler be create_console_handler with level as log_level
    Let root_logger be add_handler with logger as root_logger and handler as console_handler
    
    If log_file is not None:
        Let file_handler be create_file_handler with file_path as log_file and level as log_level
        Set root_logger to add_handler with logger as root_logger and handler as file_handler
    
    Return root_logger

Process called "setup_ai_logging" that takes log_level as LogLevel and log_file as String returns Logger:
    Let ai_logger be create_logger with name as "ai_system"
    Set ai_logger.level to log_level
    
    Let ai_handler be create_ai_handler with level as log_level
    Set ai_logger to add_handler with logger as ai_logger and handler as ai_handler
    
    Let json_handler be create_json_handler with file_path as log_file and level as log_level
    Set ai_logger to add_handler with logger as ai_logger and handler as json_handler
    
    Return ai_logger

Process called "setup_development_logging" that returns Logger:
    Let dev_logger be create_logger with name as "development"
    Set dev_logger.level to DEBUG
    
    Let console_handler be create_console_handler with level as DEBUG
    Set console_handler.formatter to create_ai_formatter
    Set dev_logger to add_handler with logger as dev_logger and handler as console_handler
    
    Let file_handler be create_file_handler with file_path as "development.log" and level as DEBUG
    Set file_handler.formatter to create_json_formatter
    Set dev_logger to add_handler with logger as dev_logger and handler as file_handler
    
    Return dev_logger

Note: Utility Functions (to be implemented in core library)
Process called "current_time" returns Float:
    Note: Returns current system time in seconds since Unix epoch
    Try:
        Return system_time_seconds
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to millisecond precision converted to seconds
        Try:
            Let milliseconds be system_time_milliseconds
            Return milliseconds divided by 1000000.0
        Catch fallback_error:
            Note: Ultimate fallback - should not happen in production
            Return 0.0

Process called "get_current_module" returns String:
    Note: Returns the name of the current module using runtime introspection
    Try:
        Let call_stack be get_call_stack
        If length of call_stack is greater than 0:
            Let current_frame be call_stack at index 0
            If current_frame contains key "module":
                Return current_frame at key "module"
        Return extract_module_from_file_path with file_path as get_current_file_path
    Catch error:
        Return "<unknown_module>"

Process called "get_current_function" returns String:
    Note: Returns the name of the current function using runtime introspection
    Try:
        Let call_stack be get_call_stack
        If length of call_stack is greater than 0:
            Let current_frame be call_stack at index 0
            If current_frame contains key "function":
                Return current_frame at key "function"
        Return "<unknown_function>"
    Catch error:
        Return "<unknown_function>"

Process called "get_current_line" returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the current line number using runtime introspection
    Try:
        Let call_stack be get_call_stack
        If length of call_stack is greater than 0:
            Let current_frame be call_stack at index 0
            If current_frame contains key "line":
                Return current_frame at key "line"
        Return 0
    Catch error:
        Return 0

Process called "replace_string" that takes string as String and old as String and new as String returns String:
    Note: Replace all occurrences of old substring with new substring
    If length of old is equal to 0:
        Return string
    
    Let result be ""
    Let i be 0
    Let string_length be length of string
    Let old_length be length of old
    
    While i is less than string_length:
        Let match_found be true
        Let j be 0
        
        Note: Check if old substring matches at current position
        While j is less than old_length and (i plus j) is less than string_length:
            If character_at_index with string as string and index as (i plus j) is not equal to character_at_index with string as old and index as j:
                Set match_found to false
                Break
            Set j to j plus 1
        
        If match_found and j is equal to old_length:
            Set result to result plus new
            Set i to i plus old_length
        Otherwise:
            Set result to result plus character_at_index with string as string and index as i
            Set i to i plus 1
    
    Return result

Process called "join_strings" that takes strings as List[String] and separator as String returns String:
    Note: Join list of strings with separator between each element
    If length of strings is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    
    If length of strings is equal to 1:
        Return strings at index 0
    
    Let result be strings at index 0
    Let i be 1
    
    While i is less than length of strings:
        Set result to result plus separator plus (strings at index i)
        Set i to i plus 1
    
    Return result

Process called "format_iso_timestamp" that takes timestamp as Float returns String:
    Note: Format timestamp as ISO 8601 string (YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SSZ)
    Try:
        Let seconds_since_epoch be floor of timestamp
        Let microseconds be floor of ((timestamp minus seconds_since_epoch) multiplied by 1000000)
        
        Note: Calculate date components from Unix timestamp
        Let days_since_epoch be floor of (seconds_since_epoch divided by 86400)
        Let seconds_today be seconds_since_epoch modulo 86400
        
        Note: Calculate date from days since epoch (1970-01-01)
        Let (year, month, day) be days_to_date with days as days_since_epoch
        
        Note: Calculate time components
        Let hour be floor of (seconds_today divided by 3600)
        Let minute be floor of ((seconds_today modulo 3600) divided by 60)
        Let second be seconds_today modulo 60
        
        Note: Format with zero padding
        Let year_str be pad_integer with value as year and width as 4
        Let month_str be pad_integer with value as month and width as 2
        Let day_str be pad_integer with value as day and width as 2
        Let hour_str be pad_integer with value as hour and width as 2
        Let minute_str be pad_integer with value as minute and width as 2
        Let second_str be pad_integer with value as second and width as 2
        
        Return year_str plus "-" plus month_str plus "-" plus day_str plus "T" plus hour_str plus ":" plus minute_str plus ":" plus second_str plus "Z"
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to simple format
        Return "1970-01-01T00:00:00Z"

Process called "format_readable_timestamp" that takes timestamp as Float returns String:
    Note: Format timestamp as human-readable string (YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS)
    Try:
        Let seconds_since_epoch be floor of timestamp
        Let days_since_epoch be floor of (seconds_since_epoch divided by 86400)
        Let seconds_today be seconds_since_epoch modulo 86400
        
        Note: Calculate date from days since epoch
        Let (year, month, day) be days_to_date with days as days_since_epoch
        
        Note: Calculate time components
        Let hour be floor of (seconds_today divided by 3600)
        Let minute be floor of ((seconds_today modulo 3600) divided by 60)
        Let second be seconds_today modulo 60
        
        Note: Format with zero padding
        Let year_str be pad_integer with value as year and width as 4
        Let month_str be pad_integer with value as month and width as 2
        Let day_str be pad_integer with value as day and width as 2
        Let hour_str be pad_integer with value as hour and width as 2
        Let minute_str be pad_integer with value as minute and width as 2
        Let second_str be pad_integer with value as second and width as 2
        
        Return year_str plus "-" plus month_str plus "-" plus day_str plus " " plus hour_str plus ":" plus minute_str plus ":" plus second_str
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to simple format
        Return "1970-01-01 00:00:00"

Process called "append_to_file" that takes path as String and content as String and encoding as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Append content to file with specified encoding
    Try:
        Note: Check if file exists and is writable
        Let file_exists be file_exists_check with path as path
        If not file_exists:
            Note: Create file if it doesn't exist
            Let create_success be create_file with path as path
            If not create_success:
                Return false
        
        Note: Open file in append mode
        Let file_handle be open_file with path as path and mode as "append" and encoding as encoding
        If file_handle is None:
            Return false
        
        Note: Write content to file
        Let write_success be write_to_file_handle with handle as file_handle and content as content
        Let close_success be close_file_handle with handle as file_handle
        
        Return write_success and close_success
    Catch error:
        Return false

Process called "merge_dictionaries" that takes dict1 as Dictionary[String, Any] and dict2 as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Merge two dictionaries, with dict2 values taking precedence over dict1
    Let result be dictionary containing
    
    Note: Copy all entries from dict1
    For each key in keys of dict1:
        Set result at key key to dict1 at key key
    
    Note: Copy all entries from dict2, overwriting dict1 values
    For each key in keys of dict2:
        Set result at key key to dict2 at key key
    
    Return result

Process called "serialize" that takes value as JSONValue returns String:
    Note: Serialize JSON value to string representation
    Match value:
        When JSONNull:
            Return "null"
        When JSONBoolean with bool_value as bool_val:
            If bool_val:
                Return "true"
            Otherwise:
                Return "false"
        When JSONNumber with number_value as num_val:
            Return float_to_string with value as num_val
        When JSONString with string_value as str_val:
            Return quote_json_string with string as str_val
        When JSONArray with array_value as arr_val:
            Return serialize_json_array with array as arr_val
        When JSONObject with object_value as obj_val:
            Return serialize_json_object with object as obj_val
        Otherwise:
            Return "null"

Process called "JSONObject" that takes fields as Dictionary[String, JSONValue] returns JSONValue:
    Note: Create a JSON object from dictionary of fields
    Return JSONObject with object_value as fields

Process called "JSONString" that takes value as String returns JSONValue:
    Note: Create a JSON string value
    Return JSONString with string_value as value

Process called "JSONNumber" that takes value as Float returns JSONValue:
    Note: Create a JSON number value
    Return JSONNumber with number_value as value

Process called "JSONNull" returns JSONValue:
    Note: Create a JSON null value
    Return JSONNull

Process called "Some" that takes value as Any returns Optional[Any]:
    Note: Wrap value in Optional type - CRITICAL for type system correctness
    Return Optional with value as value and has_value as true

Process called "None" returns Optional[Any]:
    Note: Return empty Optional type - CRITICAL for type system correctness
    Return Optional with value as none and has_value as false

Process called "length" that takes lst as List[Any] returns Integer:
    Note: Implementation depends on core list operations
    Return 0

Process called "keys" that takes dict as Dictionary[String, Any] returns List[String]:
    Note: Implementation depends on core dictionary operations
    Return list containing

Process called "add" that takes lst as List[Any] and item as Any returns List[Any]:
    Note: Implementation depends on core list operations
    Return lst

Process called "remove" that takes lst as List[Any] and index as Integer returns List[Any]:
    Note: Implementation depends on core list operations
    Return lst

Note: Additional helper functions for logging implementation

Process called "system_time_seconds" returns Float:
    Note: Returns current system time in seconds since Unix epoch using pure Runa
    Try:
        Note: Use essential runtime call for time
        Return system_call_time_current
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to millisecond precision
        Let milliseconds be system_call_time_high_res
        Return (milliseconds as Float) divided by 1000.0

Process called "system_time_milliseconds" returns Float:
    Note: Returns current system time in milliseconds since Unix epoch using pure Runa
    Try:
        Note: Use essential runtime call for time
        Let seconds be system_call_time_current
        Return seconds multiplied by 1000.0
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to high-resolution time
        Let nanoseconds be system_call_time_high_res
        Return (nanoseconds as Float) divided by 1000000.0

Process called "get_call_stack" returns List[Dictionary[String, Any]]:
    Note: Returns current call stack for introspection using pure Runa
    Try:
        Note: Use essential runtime call for call stack
        Return system_call_reflection_get_call_stack with depth as 10
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback: return empty call stack
        Return list containing

Process called "get_current_file_path" returns String:
    Note: Returns path of currently executing file using pure Runa
    Try:
        Note: Use reflection runtime call for source location
        Let call_stack be system_call_reflection_get_call_stack with depth as 1
        If length of call_stack is greater than 0:
            Let top_frame be call_stack at index 0
            If top_frame contains key "file_path":
                Return top_frame at key "file_path"
        Return "<unknown_file>"
    Catch error:
        Return "<unknown_file>"

Process called "extract_module_from_file_path" that takes file_path as String returns String:
    Note: Extract module name from file path
    If length of file_path is equal to 0:
        Return "<unknown_module>"
    
    Note: Find last slash and last dot
    Let last_slash be find_last_character with string as file_path and char as "/"
    Let last_dot be find_last_character with string as file_path and char as "."
    
    Let start_index be 0
    If last_slash is not equal to negative 1:
        Set start_index to last_slash plus 1
    
    Let end_index be length of file_path
    If last_dot is not equal to negative 1 and last_dot is greater than start_index:
        Set end_index to last_dot
    
    If end_index is greater than start_index:
        Return substring with string as file_path and start as start_index and length as (end_index minus start_index)
    
    Return "<unknown_module>"

Process called "character_at_index" that takes string as String and index as Integer returns String:
    Note: Get character at specific index in string
    If index is less than 0 or index is greater than or equal to length of string:
        Return ""
    Try:
        Return substring with string as string and start as index and length as 1
    Catch error:
        Return ""

Process called "days_to_date" that takes days as Integer returns Tuple[Integer, Integer, Integer]:
    Note: Convert days since Unix epoch to (year, month, day)
    Note: Unix epoch is 1970-01-01, which was day 0
    
    Let year be 1970
    Let remaining_days be days
    
    Note: Handle years
    While remaining_days is greater than or equal to 365:
        Let days_in_year be 365
        If is_leap_year with year as year:
            Set days_in_year to 366
        
        If remaining_days is greater than or equal to days_in_year:
            Set remaining_days to remaining_days minus days_in_year
            Set year to year plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Note: Handle months
    Let month be 1
    Let days_in_months be list containing 31, 28, 31, 30, 31, 30, 31, 31, 30, 31, 30, 31
    
    Note: Adjust February for leap year
    If is_leap_year with year as year:
        Set days_in_months at index 1 to 29
    
    For i from 0 to 11:
        Let days_in_current_month be days_in_months at index i
        If remaining_days is greater than or equal to days_in_current_month:
            Set remaining_days to remaining_days minus days_in_current_month
            Set month to month plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
    
    Let day be remaining_days plus 1
    Return (year, month, day)

Process called "is_leap_year" that takes year as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if year is a leap year
    If year modulo 400 is equal to 0:
        Return true
    If year modulo 100 is equal to 0:
        Return false
    If year modulo 4 is equal to 0:
        Return true
    Return false

Process called "pad_integer" that takes value as Integer and width as Integer returns String:
    Note: Pad integer with leading zeros to specified width
    Let str_value be integer_to_string with value as value
    Let current_length be length of str_value
    
    If current_length is greater than or equal to width:
        Return str_value
    
    Let padding_needed be width minus current_length
    Let padding be ""
    For i from 0 to padding_needed minus 1:
        Set padding to padding plus "0"
    
    Return padding plus str_value

Process called "float_to_string" that takes value as Float returns String:
    Note: Convert float to string representation using pure Runa
    Try:
        Note: Use essential runtime call for string conversion
        Return system_call_object_to_string with obj as value
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback: basic float to string conversion
        If value is equal to 0.0:
            Return "0.0"
        Otherwise if value is less than 0:
            Return "-" plus float_to_string_pure with value as (negative value)
        Otherwise:
            Return float_to_string_pure with value as value

Process called "integer_to_string" that takes value as Integer returns String:
    Note: Convert integer to string representation using pure Runa
    Try:
        Note: Use essential runtime call for string conversion
        Return system_call_object_to_string with obj as value
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback: basic integer to string conversion
        If value is equal to 0:
            Return "0"
        Otherwise if value is less than 0:
            Return "-" plus integer_to_string_pure with value as (negative value)
        Otherwise:
            Return integer_to_string_pure with value as value

Process called "find_last_character" that takes string as String and char as String returns Integer:
    Note: Find last occurrence of character in string, return -1 if not found
    Let i be length of string minus 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        If character_at_index with string as string and index as i is equal to char:
            Return i
        Set i to i minus 1
    Return negative 1

Process called "substring" that takes string as String and start as Integer and length as Integer returns String:
    Note: Extract substring from string using pure Runa
    Try:
        Note: Use essential runtime call for string operations
        Return system_call_character_at with string as string and index as start
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback: pure Runa substring implementation
        If start is less than 0 or length is less than or equal to 0:
            Return ""
        If start is greater than or equal to length of string:
            Return ""
        
        Let end_index be start plus length
        If end_index is greater than length of string:
            Set end_index to length of string
        
        Let result be ""
        For i from start to end_index minus 1:
            Let char be character_at_index with string as string and index as i
            Set result to result plus char
        
        Return result

Process called "file_exists_check" that takes path as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if file exists at given path using pure Runa
    Try:
        Note: Use essential runtime call for file operations
        Let handle be system_call_file_open with path as path and mode as "r"
        If handle is greater than or equal to 0:
            Let close_result be system_call_file_close with handle as handle
            Return true
        Otherwise:
            Return false
    Catch error:
        Return false

Process called "create_file" that takes path as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Create a new file at given path using pure Runa
    Try:
        Note: Use essential runtime call for file creation
        Return system_call_file_create with path as path and mode as 0644
    Catch error:
        Return false

Process called "open_file" that takes path as String and mode as String and encoding as String returns Optional[Any]:
    Note: Open file and return file handle using pure Runa
    Try:
        Note: Use essential runtime call for file operations
        Let handle be system_call_file_open with path as path and mode as mode
        If handle is greater than or equal to 0:
            Return Some with value as handle
        Return None
    Catch error:
        Return None

Process called "write_to_file_handle" that takes handle as Any and content as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Write content to file handle using pure Runa
    Try:
        Note: Use essential runtime call for file operations
        Let content_bytes be convert_string_to_bytes with text as content
        Return system_call_file_write with handle as handle and offset as 0 and data as content_bytes
    Catch error:
        Return false

Note: Pure Runa utility functions for logging
Process called "float_to_string_pure" that takes value as Float returns String:
    Note: Pure Runa implementation of float to string conversion
    If value is equal to 0.0:
        Return "0.0"
    
    Let integer_part be value as Integer
    Let decimal_part be value minus (integer_part as Float)
    
    Let integer_str be integer_to_string_pure with value as integer_part
    Let decimal_str be ""
    
    If decimal_part is greater than 0.0:
        Set decimal_str to "."
        Let decimal_digits be 6
        For i from 0 to decimal_digits minus 1:
            Set decimal_part to decimal_part multiplied by 10.0
            Let digit be decimal_part as Integer
            Set decimal_str to decimal_str plus (digit as String)
            Set decimal_part to decimal_part minus (digit as Float)
            If decimal_part is equal to 0.0:
                Break
    
    Return integer_str plus decimal_str

Process called "integer_to_string_pure" that takes value as Integer returns String:
    Note: Pure Runa implementation of integer to string conversion
    If value is equal to 0:
        Return "0"
    
    Let digits be "0123456789"
    Let result be ""
    Let abs_value be absolute_value with value as value
    
    While abs_value is greater than 0:
        Let digit_index be abs_value modulo 10
        Let digit_char be character_at with string as digits and index as digit_index
        Set result to digit_char plus result
        Set abs_value to abs_value divided by 10
    
    Return result

Process called "convert_string_to_bytes" that takes text as String returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Convert string to byte array using pure Runa
    Let bytes be list containing
    For i from 0 to (length of text minus 1):
        Let char be character_at_index with string as text and index as i
        Let byte_value be character_to_ascii with char as char
        Add byte_value to bytes
    Return bytes

